ts from Thoreau's writings about trees, paired with over sixty of the author's photographs. Thoreau's words are as vivid now as they were in 1890, when an English naturalist wrote that he was unusually able to "to preserve the flashing forest colors in unfading light." Thoreau and the Language of Trees shows that Thoreau, with uncanny foresight, believed trees were essential to the preservation of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 4aanthology. 4aconnection to trees. 4aenglish naturalist. 4aessay collection. 4aessential ecosystem. 4ahiker. 4ahiking. 4alively essay. 4anatural science appreciation. 4anatural science. 4anature appreciation. 4anature. 4aphilosopher. 4aphilosophy. 4aportrait of a tree. 70(DE-601)1049283520(DE-588)4232002-1aSprachegMotiv2gnd 70(DE-601)1058355010(DE-588)4112675-0aBaumgMotiv2gnd 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520967311.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles